A team of Czech and German scientists test new compounds to stop the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works with viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact prevails against the disadvantage that the connection to common viral variants does not work as strong as one of the already existing drugs.
AIDS disease cannot be cured.
However, the patient’s combination of medications can extend life and prevent the reproduction of HIV viruses in the body.
However, their intake is accompanied by a whole number of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of the viral proliferation has also resulted in the development of resistant viruses, against which no drugs are more effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, from the VSCHT (Chemical and Technological College) Prague as well as from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to cope with the virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances called metal-carborans act on the protein responsible for the reproduction of the HIV virus.
The metal carborans are compounds of bor, hydrogen, carbon and kobalt.
These compounds block the viral proliferation in other ways than all the drugs used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists come to new ‘upgrade’ compounds, which were prepared on the basis of the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their bond to the viral protein.
The metal carborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-shaped boxes consisting of bor, hydrogen and carbon atoms and linked by a metal atom, in this case kobalt.
