Married couples who violate this policy must expect enormous fines — up to their three-fold annual salary in some regions — and discrimination at their workplace.
Chinese representatives have attributed to this policy that the critical claim of national natural resources could be avoided, while human rights representatives have condemned misuse in the implementation of the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who have already had a child to give up.
Many couples were also allowed to perform gender-selective abortions, resulting in an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their attitude towards one-child policy.
In 2004, they accepted more exceptions to the rule—including urban residents, ethnic minorities and cases in which both husband and wife were single children—and in 2007 the tone of many harsh slogans was shrinked.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research at the University of Beijing said that government representatives recently even discussed more radical changes, for example, allowing couples to have two children with a partner a single child.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births in July.
Posters that taught families to have only one child were almost overnight replaced by guidelines that detailed who comes into question for a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city administration has sent urban staff and family planning volunteers to visit couples at home and pull information sheets under the doors.
She also asked to provide psychological and financial advice for those who have more than one child.
The reaction was not just encouraging, family planning representatives said.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a rural small town in the outskirts of Shanghai said that there is a rise in the requests of couples who want a second child after the start of the campaign, the city districts don’t report any change.
In the municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, for example, only four to five applications are submitted per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that the number of births expected for 2010 in the city will still be around 165,000 despite the campaign -- a little higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the Family Planning Committee of the Shanghai Caolu Municipality, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don’t want to have children anymore.
They want to give their first best, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would like to have two children and this was legally permitted.
But they own, as many Chinese, only a small health and life insurance of the government.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West erroneously assess one-child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a building engineer whose wife is pregnant in the seventh month with her first child.
Yes, we’re stolen the opportunity to have more than one child.
The problem is not just in a policy.
The problem is money.
Other couples indicate psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the staff manager, said she just wanted a child because she was also a single child. "We were the center of the family and used to everyone cared about us.
We are not accustomed to taking care of others and do not really want it.”
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old man belonging to a translation company, said it unblind.
For parents from the middle age with a double career through which the birth rate decreases, he said, it turns to be successful and for that you have to be selfish.
The age group of today’s 20- to 39-year-olds grew up by seeing their parents struggle during the early days of the Chinese capitalism experiment and they don’t want such a life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child, he said, poses enormous demands to the time of the parents.
A mother must give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there is the space question -- "You must rebuild your apartment" -- and the life plan -- "If the child is 9 months old, you must already have a resume for the best pre-schools."
Most of his friends are ready to go through this once, Chen said, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to reach a higher standard of life, he said.
We don’t want to bring too many victims.
United Nations Group Plans Emissions Reduction Plan
The UN-sponsored climate conference, which has so far been distinguished by wild poses and mutual accusations, on Friday again highlighted with the publication of a document that marks a ambitious reduction of greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with the industrial nations to bear the greatest burden in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final policy agreement on greenhouse gas regulation, has both denied the remaining obstacles and showed the way forward.
But it was seen as an important progress in a negotiation that comes out as next week more than 100 top politicians from all over the world will arrive in Copenhagen.
The text, formulated by a specific UN working group, is silent about the amount of money that wealthy countries should give to the poor countries in order to manage the global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key issues, including how industrial and large emerging countries can limit their carbon emissions and how high the upper limit of the global temperature rise would be contributed by policy makers.
The process will be given great flexibility, says John Coequyt, chief representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who designed the six-page document, has summarized a 180-page negotiation text to focus on what the leading UN climate representative, Yvo de Boer, has called “the big whole.”
It shows the groundbreaking of a possible agreement in which industrial nations would jointly reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 border values, while bigger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent in the same period.
Together, countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community also pushed on Friday’s talks through its commitment to allocate $3.6 billion per year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impacts of climate change – from the master of floods and droughts to the prevention of deforestation.
The Friday, however, brought the same verbal fireworks that the talks had determined last week.
The U.S. Climate Commissioner Todd Stern has rejected formulations that require binding reductions of greenhouse gas emissions for industrial countries, compared to voluntary reductions for larger developing countries, if they are not funded by industrial nations.
This train announced that the Obama administration is running a harder line with China than the representative of the Bush administration not even two years ago.
The United States will not sign any agreement without the rise of larger emerging countries and taking action, according to the star, who also complained that the text is not going far enough, to ensure that the reductions could also be confirmed by outside countries.
Star gave his opinion an hour after the statement of Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei, who said that the leading U.S. climate dealers either lacked "the reason" or it was "highly irresponsible" from him that he said at the beginning of the week that the United States would not help China financially to cope with global warming.
As the future economic direction of the great world powers is on the ground, breaks have emerged both within the industrial nations and between the industrial nations and the emerging countries.
The current struggle refers equally to the rescue of individual economies as well as to the rescue of the planet, with China and the United States standing for their respective commitments, while poorest countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take more courageous measures.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it is not surprising that the great powers are struggling for who should bear the costs for the freezing of greenhouse gas emissions, as even the affected countries have moved to act more aggressively to take the countries with very high greenhouse gas taxes to the responsibility for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic domination will develop, says Ulate, who also works as a regional climate change adviser for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the effects of climate change said they would continue to struggle for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although the leading participants say that the talks will lead to a political agreement in the best case.
The Alliance of Small Islands States with 43 members submitted a 24-sided draft agreement early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who leads the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the offensive of the small island states "exercits political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now united and demands action from emerging countries, such as China and India.
The talks got a new urgency as the delegates focused on the fact that most open questions need to be clarified before the government leaders arrived in order to reach an agreement.
High-ranking representatives, such as the Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Vice-Ministry, rise their aircraft and walk through the Bella Center to meetings behind closed doors and press conferences to remove claims that will be negotiated during the next week.
The purely scale of the assembly—13,000 people go and go out in the congress center every day, guitar actors host night shows in which they make fun about the countries that they think are betrayed and sold, and contracts are hand in hand rather than by email—is already a challenge.
The intensity is just building up: almost all important ministers are now here and from Wednesday 60 leaders will be in Copenhagen.
We come to the Oberliga, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president for global policy of the organization Conservation International.
