Support for brake maneuver in critical situations is now mandatory
As at the time with the anti-blocking brake system ABS and as it is now happening with the stability control ESP, the emergency brake assistance systems must become a mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly approved passenger cars and small-sized carriers, for the remaining vehicles a carrier period was established until the end of February 2011.
The measure adopted by the European Union is aimed at improving the protection of passengers, but these brake systems can also help prevent many accidents due to their functioning.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exercise more pressure on the brakes in the case of a critical brake maneuver that recognizes the system using the brake strength performed by the driver on the brake pedal.
However, this system does not exercise that pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident did not come to the brake pedal before the collision, and half of them had not broken down with full strength.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, on the contrary, invades the brake system with maximum strength and thus reduces the brake time and thus the brake distance a car holds down during the brake process.
According to a EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents in which fighters are injured could be prevented every year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assistants.
There would even be fewer accidents - one is expected that one in four accidents with human damage could be prevented - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (through a radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time it already exercises a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver then responds, the system will help him increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already inevitable, the brake assistant exercises the maximum pressure on the brakes in order to keep the damage as low as possible.
