New Programs for Vehicle Review
In these days of crashes and accidents, not only the car workshops deserve
Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are thrown into the workshops, where an assessor has to assess the damages arising and the costs for the repair.
No one accident is the same and calculating the costs for the parts and working hours can be a long and complicated task.
The calculation of the repair costs of between €20,000 and €30,000 per hand, including parts and working hours, can take up to two or three hours.
In contrast, with the support of the latest computer tools, it is a matter of minutes.
That’s why almost 100% of reviewers use this type of systems.
The service and application providers for the assessment of accidents and restoration collect the information they receive from the manufacturers to process it afterwards and offer it to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American group Solera, is the market leader; 80% of all reviews are made with their products.
The other two companies that compete with the tool market for review and reporting are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data that the manufacturers provide is nothing but simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, sales manager of Audatex, it is working with 63 manufacturers and importers, each of them providing the information in a different format.
Furthermore, the amount of data to be processed is increasing to the point that in the last five years more versions, variants and motorizations have come to the market than in the entire fifteen years before.
Once a new car comes to the market, the work begins for the companies.
It is a difficult task, because every single of the Eighty Thousand Vehicle Parts must be catalogued and its price is entered.
In addition, each model creates a “intelligent” graphic image on which you can “click” on different parts of the vehicle.
If it’s a much-sold model, the work can be completed within a week if the procedure progresses rapidly.
If it’s a less common car, it can take up to three or four months. Currently, Audatex has full information on 99.2% of the cars sold in Spain.
Among the more exclusive models, for example, they have information about the Porsche models, but not about Ferrari or Lamborghini.
In terms of the car park on the streets, it is over 99%.
Audatex has eight distributed centers worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, the United States, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) and each of them has specialized in specific brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics professionals) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests €90 million annually in the development of these databases.
Each month they collect 2.5 million data and their customers receive updates every second day.
The development of this enormous flow of information enables companies to use it in different ways and thus offer different products.
The most common use is the use for repairs and repairs, however, depending on country, there are also tools for managing rubbish parts or for calculating the error or residual value of a car.
The only company that informs a driver about the value of the used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer this offer in Spain but in the United States.
By reviewing the products that Audatex offers, you can easily find an overview of the type of support it provides to industry experts.
